[2] UK (Somerset, England)
Date: Mon 5 Aug 2013
Source: This Is Somerset [edited]
http://www.thisissomerset.co.uk/Breaking-news-Risk-measles-outbreak-Glastonbury/story-19614795-detail/story.html#axzz2bCdBF6Kn


Central Somerset parents are being advised to get their children vaccinated against measles. Outbreaks of the disease, which is highly infectious, have been reported in Street and Glastonbury. Public Health advisers say they have received 11 new notifications of measles in children and young people aged from 10-24 in the area since July [2013]. Those affected live in the Street and Glastonbury areas and were all unvaccinated. Prior to July there had been just one case of measles in Somerset in the 1st half of this year [2013].

Now parents are being urged to make sure their children are fully vaccinated with both doses of the measles, mumps and rubella (MMR) vaccine. Stewart Brock, Public Health Specialist at Somerset County Council, said: "By getting immunised you protect yourself, or your child, but you are also protecting other more vulnerable people in the community who could become seriously ill if they catch the disease. Over the past 2 months, we've been working hard with NHS and public health colleagues on an MMR catch up programme, looking to identify anyone aged 10-16 years old who has not had any MMR vaccine, so they can be offered the jab."

Early symptoms of the disease are a runny nose, high fever and tiny white spots in the mouth. After a few days a rash appears, usually beginning behind the ears, then spreading across the face, neck and rest of the body.

Measles is most common among children aged between 1 and 4, although anyone not vaccinated against measles can catch it. It can be especially dangerous to like newborn babies, pregnant women as well as patients on cancer and organ transplant drugs.

Cllr Christine Lawrence, Chair of Somerset Health and Wellbeing Board, said: "We want to encourage parents and young people to ensure they are up to date with their vaccinations. Measles should never be taken lightly, and you can never tell when you have passed it on to someone in whom it would cause serious, maybe fatal disease."

--
