[3] UK (HPR)
Date: Fri 9 Aug 2013
Source: Health Protection Report, Volume 7, no.32 [summ., edited]
http://www.hpa.org.uk/hpr/archives/2013/news3213.htm#msls1306


The decline in the number of laboratory-confirmed cases of measles in England observed in May [2013] continued in June [2013], with a total of 113 cases, bringing the total since the start of the year [2013] to 1287 cases. The north-west remains the most affected region, although numbers have increased in the south-west and in London). The highest proportion of cases were reported in children aged 1-4 years (26/113; 23 percent), a shift from the 10-14 year age group most affected earlier in the year. The proportion of cases reported in June [2013] aged 10-16 years (17/113) -- the age group targeted in the on-going MMR catch-up campaign -- was lower than in any month since February 2012.

So far this year [2013], 260 (20 percent) cases have been associated with secondary school outbreaks. Small outbreaks have also been reported from "hard-to-reach" populations with known low vaccine coverage such as the travelling community and the ultra-Orthodox Jewish community in north London. Overall, 257 (20 percent) of all cases in 2013 were admitted to hospital, including 39 with complications including pneumonia, meningitis and gastroenteritis.

In England, most of the cases with an onset date in June [2013] that have been genotyped have been shown to be MVs/Taunton.GBR/27.12/[D8], with sporadic cases of other D8 and genotype B3 strains.

As previously reported, the shift towards cases in secondary school age groups during 2013 is likely to be due to the fall in coverage of MMR between 1999 and 2005. To reduce the risk of larger outbreaks of measles in the next academic year, Public Health England, the Department of Health and NHS England announced an MMR catch-up programme in late April [2013]. The campaign has targeted children aged between 10 and 16 years who have a record of incomplete MMR vaccination, or none at all. Returns from the NHS Areas Teams confirm that almost 5000 practices have already signed up to participate in the programme. The service involves sending letters from general practices inviting under-vaccinated children to attend the surgery for vaccination. The primary target population was the estimated 8 percent of that age group who had received no vaccine (around 1/3rd of a million). Secondary targets included a similar number of that age group who had received one dose of MMR, and a similar number of children in other age groups.

Data has been extracted from just over 2000 practices (around 1/4th of the total) on the MMR status of children turning 10 to 16 years of age in June 2013. Comparing this with children aged 9-15 years in 2012, suggests that the proportion recorded as unvaccinated fell by around 1.3 percent (representing around 16 000 children in the participating practices). If this progress was replicated nationally this suggests that around 57 000 unvaccinated children have received MMR since last year [2012]. The proportion recorded as having received 2 doses of MMR has increased by 1.6 percent. Although some of this may represent data cleaning, this scale of increase is consistent with the vaccine ordering data, which suggests that around 200 000 extra doses have been used. So far, most vaccination has been conducted in primary care, although schools campaigns have been conducted in response to local outbreaks in many areas. Plans are being developed to sustain these activities and to undertake specific programmes in some schools during the next academic year.

