[4] China (Taiwan)
Date: Wed 7 Aug 2013
Source: Taipei Times [edited]
http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2013/08/07/2003569130


The Centers for Disease Control (CDC) yesterday announced this year's [2013's] 2nd confirmed case of measles, advising families with small children to get them vaccinated as scheduled and young people going on vacation to visit travel clinics before going to regions with measles epidemics.

A 25-year-old male with no recent travel history and an unknown vaccination history started to develop symptoms of coughing and a runny nose on 28 Jul 2013, and a skin rash developed 2 days later. He tested positive for measles yesterday [6 Aug 2013], CDC official Liu Ting-ping said. Of the 148 people who have had close contact with the patient, 43 have been confirmed to show no symptoms, with the remainder still under observation, Liu said. Liu Yu-lun, a disease prevention physician working at the CDC, said the man is the 2nd case of locally acquired measles this year [2013].

The CDC said that neighboring countries, such as China and some Southeast Asian nations, as well as some European countries, are in the throes of measles outbreaks, adding that because measles virus is easily spread between countries, children older than one year old are advised to receive the MMR vaccine immediately. "It should be noted that both of this year's cases involve young people, as the 1st case was a person also in her 20s," Liu Yu-lun said.

The immunity provided by the vaccine might wane over time, the CDC said, advising young people to visit travel clinics to be tested and receive the vaccine 2 to 4 weeks before flying if it is required. Meanwhile, the CDC also issued warnings to those who plan to travel to high-risk areas for bacillary dysentery, as the center has seen 5 cases of bacillary dysentery infection imported from Cambodia in the past month alone [July to August 2013].

[Byline: Alison Hsiao]

