[5] Canada (British Columbia)
Date: Thu 8 Aug 2013
Source: Global News [edited]
http://globalnews.ca/news/769709/warning-after-rise-in-measles-cases-in-fraser-valley-communities/


Fraser Health is warning people living in 6 Fraser Valley [British Columbia] communities after a spike in measles cases. The increase is in low immunized areas of the region, including Abbotsford, Mission, Chilliwack, Agassiz, Harrison Hot Springs and Hope. In the most recent incident, up to 60 women and newborns were exposed to the virus in a post-natal unit at the Abbotsford Regional Hospital and Cancer Centre by a visitor. The most recent took place in April 2010.

Last month [July 2013], Vancouver Coastal Health had issued a warning after a measles outbreak in Whistler and Pemberton [British Columbia]. That outbreak came just weeks after 3 people were infected with measles on Bowen Island [British Columbia].

Fraser Health spokesperson Tasleem Juma says the best way to protect yourself from measles is to get vaccinated. Measles is a very contagious virus. It spreads easily through air when an infected person breathes, coughs, or sneezes. Symptoms of measles include fever, cough, runny nose, and red and inflamed eyes. These are followed by a rash, which starts 1st on the face and neck, and spreads to the chest, arms and legs, and lasts at least 3 days. Anyone who may be experiencing these symptoms should see their doctor and notify the clinic before arriving to prevent the spread of the disease.

