[6] Australia (Victoria)
Date: Thu 8 Aug 2013
Source: The Age [edited]
http://www.theage.com.au/victoria/measles-detected-sparking-outbreak-fears-20130808-2ri3a.html


Victoria's most senior medical officer has warned of a potential measles outbreak after an infected 26-year-old man travelled through several public crowded locations in Melbourne. Chief Health Officer Rosemary Lester said it was essential Victorians were aware of the signs and symptoms of measles in light of the recent case that may have exposed a large number of Melburnians to the illness. "While this case -- a 26-year-old East Brunswick man -- is now recovering, it is possible he may have infected others before being diagnosed," Dr Lester said. The man saw a movie at the Hoyts cinema at Northland on the afternoon of Thursday [1 Aug 2013], and also attended an East Brunswick medical practice on the morning of Saturday [3 Aug 2013], before being diagnosed.

The illness usually begins with common cold symptoms such as fever, sore throat, red eyes and a cough. The characteristic measles rash usually begins 3 to 7 days after the 1st symptoms, generally starting on the face and then spreading to the rest of the body. Anyone developing these symptoms is advised to ring ahead to their GP or hospital and alert them that they have fever and a rash.

Dr Lester urged parents to be on the lookout for signs and symptoms in children, who often suffered complications from infection. "Measles is a highly infectious viral disease that can cause serious illness, particularly in very young children and adults," she said. The measles vaccine, given as a combination with other vaccines, is currently recommended on the National Immunisation Program as a 2 dose schedule for children between 12 months and 4 years of age.

